<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Adapted from the i<span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">ntroduction</span> to </em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668066591" class="external" target="_blank">The <span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Living </span><span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Mountain</span></a><em> by Nan Shepherd. <span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Introduction</span> copyright © 2011 by <span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Robert</span> <span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Macfarlane</span>. Reprinted by permission of <span class="c-mrkdwn__highlight">Scribner</span>, an imprint of Simon &amp; Schuster, LLC. Featured painting: detail from “The Cairngorms From Aviemore,” by James Torrington Bell.”</em></p>
										
																				
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/robert-macfarlane/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_1097-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/IMG_1097-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Robert Macfarlane" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/robert-macfarlane/">Robert Macfarlane</a></h6>
													Robert MacFarlane is the author of internationally best-selling and award-winning books about landscape, nature and people including <em>Underland</em>, <em>The Old Ways</em>, <em>Landmarks</em>, and (with artist Jackie Morris) <em>The Lost Words</em>. He is a Fellow of Emmanuel College, Cambridge.																									</div>
